<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="164" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,311,1622,1648]" box="[189,311,1622,1648]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,311,1622,1648]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,311,1622,1648]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[188,1400,1668,1871]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
The new species is close to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Harris, 1780)" baseAuthorityName="Harris" baseAuthorityYear="1780" box="[525,895,1668,1695]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vicana">
<emphasis box="[525,717,1669,1694]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">Drymeia vicana</emphasis>
(Harris, 1780)
</taxonomicName>
, which also has 4 postsutural dorsocentral setae, prealar absent and densely long-haired eyes. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sorokina &amp; Pont" authorityYear="2022" box="[920,1047,1704,1730]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Drymeia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="164" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ziegleri">
<emphasis box="[920,1047,1704,1730]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">D. ziegleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a larger black species with thin, elongate proboscis, mid femur slightly curved ventrally and with 3 short ventral spines closer to the middle, a row of long anteroventral setae on the apical ⅔ and a row of very long posteroventral setae; the male has the anepimeron and katepimeron bare; hind femur without long and strong posteroventrals; hind tibia with a small ventral apical prong, without apical posteroventral seta.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="164" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,325,1910,1936]" box="[189,325,1910,1936]" pageId="6" pageNumber="164">
